The Ultimate Senior Automation Interview Series: Episode 1 — Abstraction vs. Interface (And Why Java 8 Changed Everything)

4 min read
Just now

--

If you have ever sat in a technical interview for a Senior Automation role, you know that interviewers love to test your foundations. They won’t just ask you, “What is an interface?” They want to know why you would choose one over the other when building a test framework, and how modern Java features altered the landscape.
Let’s break this down so simply that a fresher can grasp the concept, but with enough depth that a senior engineer can use it to ace their next system design round.
The Real-World Mental Model
Before we look at code, let’s get our analogies straight.

• Abstract Class is an Identity (What something IS): Imagine a template for a Car. Every car is a vehicle. It has a chassis, an engine, and wheels. You can’t just buy a generic “car” — you buy a specific implementation like a Tesla or a Ford.

• Interface is a Capability (What something CAN DO): Imagine a GPS or a Bluetooth module. A car can have GPS. A smartphone can have GPS. A smartwatch can have GPS. These items aren’t related by family, but they all share the capability to track location.
