Interviewer showing a picture of an Abstract Class and an Interface before Java 8. Pam: “They’re the same picture.” (Spoiler: They weren’t, but Java 8 made them closer cousins than ever!)Why Java 8 Changed Everything
In 2014, Java 8 dropped a bombshell: Default and Static Methods. Suddenly, interfaces could have concrete methods with actual code blocks.
Why did Java do this?
Backward compatibility. Java wanted to introduce lambda expressions and stream APIs. If they added a new method to the existing Collection interface without default implementations, every single framework and library on Earth utilizing Java collections would have instantly broken.
With default methods, you can add new functionality to interfaces without breaking the classes that implement them.
public interface WebDriverSpec {
// Traditional Abstract Method
void launchBrowser(); // Java 8 Default Method - Providing a default behavior!
default void takeScreenshot() {
System.out.println
("Taking a screenshot using generic robot capabilities...");
}
}
Automation Framework Relatability: Design Patterns
In Senior Automation roles, your value lies in how you architect frameworks (like Page Object Models or Hybrid Frameworks). Let’s look at how we apply these two concepts in a real automation framework.
1. The Abstract Class Application (The Base Page / Base Test)
You use an abstract class when you want to share common state and default setup/teardown logic across your tests.
/ Reference concept inspired by standard TestNG/Selenium architectures
public abstract class BaseTest {
protected WebDriver driver; // Shared instance variable @BeforeMethod
public void setup() {
// Shared concrete logic
driver = new ChromeDriver();
driver.manage().window().maximize();
}
@AfterMethod
public void tearDown() {
if (driver != null) {
driver.quit();
}
}
// Abstract method: Every test class must define its own test steps
public abstract void runTestSteps();
}
2. The Interface Application (The Plugin Architecture)
What if some of your tests need to log defects directly to Jira upon failure, or some page components need custom JavaScript executing capabilities? You don’t want to force every test to have these capabilities, so you create interfaces.
public interface JiraReportable {
void logBugToJira(String issueSummary); // Java 8 Default method providing helper utility out-of-the-box
default String formatIssueString(String testName, String error) {
return "[AUTOMATION FAILURE] " + testName + " failed due to: " + error;
}
}
If a specific LoginTest class needs Jira logging, it simply implements JiraReportable. If it doesn’t, it ignores it. This keeps your framework decoupled and highly modular.
The Interview Checklist: How to answer like a Senior
If an interviewer asks you this question, structure your answer like this to show senior-level maturity:

• Define the Core Difference: State that Abstract Classes define an identity/hierarchy (is-a), while Interfaces define contracts/capabilities (can-do).

• Highlight Multiple Inheritance: Emphasize that Java classes can only inherit from one class, making Abstract classes a precious architectural commitment. Interfaces allow flexible, multi-capability mix-ins.

• Acknowledge Java 8+ Evolution: Explain that the line blurred with default and static methods (and later Java 9 private interface methods), shifting the decision focus away from “code vs no code” to “state vs statelessness”. Interfaces still cannot hold instance states (variables), whereas abstract classes can.

• Give Framework Examples: Tie it back to automation instantly (e.g., BasePage abstract class vs an ElementActions or VisualVerifiable interface).
